<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: YAROSLAVSKY OPPOSES PERMANENT ETHICS PANEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky said Tuesday that he thinks a 
permanent city ethics commission would be too expensive. 
</P>
<P>
Yaroslavsky said he agreed that an ethics panel, as proposed by a blue-ribbon 
panel appointed by Mayor Tom Bradley, is needed. But he dismissed as "out of 
the question" a plan to give the commission authority to hire lawyers to 
conduct investigations without approval of the city attorney or the council. 
</P>
<P>
"I have seen enough $3 (million), $4 million bills from private attorneys," 
Yaroslavsky said. "No department in the city of Los Angeles has a call on the 
city's general fund in this way," he said. "(Police Chief) Daryl Gates, who has 
a much more serious problem to deal with than the ethics commission will ever 
have to deal with, doesn't have the right to call on the general fund for 
unlimited sums of money to police gang violence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
January 13, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
Ethics panel -- A Dec. 20 Times article incorrectly stated Los Angeles City 
Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky's position on the creation of a permanent city 
ethics commission. Yaroslavsky said he supports the commission. 
</P>
