<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; 
</P>
<P>
FAMILY-HELP PLAN GOING FULL STEAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEN HALL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A spokesman for Southern California Edison was on one line, a needy family on 
the other. 
</P>
<P>
"Both seemed hesitant to talk, but they got over it after talking for about two 
minutes," Irvine Temporary Housing's Louise Wagner said. "Now, it turns out, 
the children in the family are all excited. They get to go for a ride in one of 
Edison's big trucks." 
</P>
<P>
This week, Wagner is once again playing matchmaker, just as she does each year 
during the holidays. She is in charge of Adopt A Family for Christmas 1989, her 
third year coordinating the program. 
</P>
<P>
"Businesses, families and individuals all play a part. The Soroptomists have 
called and are taking three families, Alderwood Basics Plus (an Irvine 
elementary school) is taking seven families, the Chamber of Commerce is 
involved, our high schools, the Irvine Medical Center. There are about 45 
families we are placing this year," Wagner said. 
</P>
<P>
Irvine Temporary Housing rents 10 apartments and two houses in the city to 
needy families, based on their ability to pay. Each of these families will also 
be adopted in the Christmas program. Their identities remain secret to save 
them from embarrassment, Wagner said. 
</P>
<P>
"Our 12 families always remain anonymous, as do many of the people involved in 
the Adopt a Family program," Wagner said. "Many people, on both sides of this 
program, simply prefer it that way. They bring food, gifts and sometimes 
clothing here and families come to pick it up." 
</P>
<P>
Others find out specific sizes for children and custom fit their donations. 
</P>
<P>
"It just depends on how each individual wants to handle it," Wagner said. 
"Sometimes we just give out phone numbers and they work it out outside the 
program." LEN HALL 
</P>
