<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE SENATE CANDIDATE ACCUSES RIVAL OF 'SPECIAL-INTEREST' TIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE LESHER, TIMES POLITICAL WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Republican State Senate candidate Ron Isles launched his first attack Tuesday 
in what could be a messy campaign by charging that Republican opponent Frank 
Hill "is moonlighting for special interests." 
</P>
<P>
Isles, a candidate for the special election to replace State Sen. William 
Campbell, issued a statement saying the Whittier assemblyman collected $52,412 
last year in gifts and honorariums. That is more than Hill's $44,000 
legislative salary, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"Where I come from, it looks like Frank Hill has a second job; he is 
moonlighting for the special interests," said Isles, a Brea City Council 
member. 
</P>
<P>
Hill did not return repeated telephone calls to his office Monday or Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Gov. George Deukmejian's announcement Tuesday that the primary for the 31st 
Senate District will be held Feb. 6 has forced the three announced Republican 
candidates into a quick campaign that has already seen Assemblyman Gil Ferguson 
(R-Newport Beach), the other Republican running for the GOP-dominated district, 
accuse Hill of being involved in a "Machiavellian scheme" to eliminate him from 
the race. 
</P>
<P>
Isles' campaign manager, Harvey Englander, promised that the issue of ethics -- 
believed heightened in the public's mind by recent scandals in Sacramento and 
Washington -- will play a major role in the race. 
</P>
<P>
Isles' statement Tuesday noted that Hill was a subject of the FBI's 
investigation into influence-peddling at the state Capitol. Hill's office was 
searched as part of the investigation, but no charges have been filed against 
him. Hill has declined to comment on the sting operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
