<P>
BONN TO EXCHANGE 4 SPIES FOR 24 WESTERNERS HELD IN E. GERMANY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BONN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In one of the biggest East-West spy swaps since World War II, Bonn will release 
four people jailed as Communist agents in exchange for 24 Westerners held in 
East Germany, West German government officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for West German President Richard von Weizsaecker said two former 
secretaries jailed after they passed state secrets to their KGB lovers had been 
pardoned. He could not say whether they had yet been freed. 
</P>
<P>
Bonn's minister for inner-German affairs, Dorothee Wilms, visiting Dresden with 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's delegation, confirmed the spy swap but would not give 
further details. 
</P>
<P>
"I hope this means the chapter of prisoners and agents is now ended," she said. 
"That is the prerequisite for the two governments to cooperate in trust." 
</P>
</TEXT>
