<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: 'MAGIC' DANDRUFF REMEDY NOT YET AVAILABLE IN AMERICA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON, AND DR. TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q. When I was in England last winter I had such terrible dandruff I went to see 
a dermatologist. He prescribed a shampoo that cleared my scalp up like magic. 
</P>
<P>
Now the problem has returned. My doctor says I have seborrheic dermatitis, but 
he didn't know what I was talking about when I mentioned the English shampoo. 
The stuff he offered isn't nearly as good. 
</P>
<P>
Please tell me what they use in Europe and how I can get some more. 
</P>
<P>
A. We can't be sure what your English doctor prescribed, but it might well have 
been Nizoral (ketoconazole) shampoo. Although this anti-fungal medicine is 
available in the United States both as a cream and as tablets, it has not yet 
been approved as a shampoo for seborrheic dermatitis or severe dandruff. 
</P>
<P>
There is growing evidence this condition is caused by a yeast infection of the 
scalp, which may explain why Nizoral shampoo is so effective. It is available 
in Belgium, Spain, Switzerland, Thailand, Singapore, South Africa and the 
United Kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
Unless you plan to travel abroad, you will have to wait for the Janssen 
pharmaceutical company to receive approval from the U.S. Food and Drug 
Administration to market its unique shampoo in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
Q. When will the FDA allow tryptophan to be sold again? I used it successfully 
for insomnia and am upset I can't buy it now. 
</P>
<P>
A. There are now more than 700 cases of EMS (eosinophilia-myalgia syndrome) 
reported in conjunction with tryptophan. This potentially lethal blood and 
muscle disorder has everyone confused. 
</P>
<P>
Although millions of people have used tryptophan safely for years, the reports 
of fever, muscle aches and high blood counts have forced the feds to pull this 
amino acid off the market. Until they get to the bottom of the mystery, no one 
should take tryptophan. 
</P>
<P>
Q. I have had asthma for 60 years, and I try to stay on top of new drugs and 
therapies for my breathing problem. Is there any newsletter that would keep me 
up to date on the latest trends in asthma treatment? 
</P>
<P>
A. We have just come across "Air Currents," a new asthma newsletter. It offers 
practical information and lists resources. For a free copy write to Air 
Currents, Dept. P; 301 East 57th St., New York, NY 10022. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA122089-0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 151383 </DOCID>
