<P>
SWIM COACH FACES SEX CHARGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MORENO VALLEY, Calif. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A children's swimming coach who met a 13-year-old girl on a so-called telephone 
"talk line" faces six felony charges of sexual misconduct with a minor, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Joseph Patrick Pennels, 27, a longtime coach of the Moreno Valley Marlins swim 
club, was charged last week with six felony counts of lewd and lascivious acts 
with a child under 14, Riverside County Assistant Dist. Atty. Guy Pittman said. 
</P>
<P>
Each charge carries a maximum penalty of three, six or eight years in prison. 
Pennels has pleaded innocent. 
</P>
<P>
The girl's mother contacted police late in November after she discovered her 
daughter missing from home late one night and found a letter in the girl's room 
that led her to believe she was having a physical relationship with Pennels. 
</P>
<P>
The Moreno Valley Marlins is a private swim team for youngsters 5 to 18 years 
old. The team competes in the San Gorgonio swim league. Pennels resigned this 
month "for personal reasons," team spokesman Chris Jones said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
